# Known (or nearly-known) facts about Sindarin

## The Corpus

- Ai na vedui Dúnadan! Mae govannen!
- Noro lim, noro lim, Asfaloth!
- Naur an edraith ammen! Naur dan i ngaurhoth!
- Annon edhellen, edro hi ammen! Fennas nogothrim, lasto beth lammen!
- Ennyn Durin Aran Moria: pedo mellon a minno. Im Narvi hain echant: Celebrimbor o Eregion teithant i thiw hin
- A Elbereth Gilthoniel / silivren penna míriel / o menel aglar elenath! / Na-chaered palan-díriel / o galadhremmin ennorath, / Fanuilos le linnathon / nef aear, sí nef aearon
- A Elbereth Gilthoniel o menel palan-diriel, le nallon sí di-nguruthos! A tiro nin, Fanuilos!
- Cuio i Pheriain anann! Aglar'ni Pheriannath! ... Daur a Berhael, Conin en Annûn, eglerio! ... Eglerio!
- Ónen i-Estel Edain, ú-chebin estel anim

- plural umlaut
- imperative -o
- future volitive -atha- for a-stems
- present -a- for a-stems (and we understand where it comes from: linna-sō "he sings" -> linnaho -> linnah -> linna)
- past -ant for a-stems
- definite article: singular *i*, plural *in*
- lenition
- vocab: LOTR, with Noldorin from Ety., strengthened by Q. cognates
- -tha as a derivation suffix for transitive verbs (from PQ -tā)
- spelling and pronunciation
- used the Mode of Beleriand, Mode of Gondor for writing
- adjectives often follow nouns, are often lenited
- relative particle *i* (attested in King's Letter, Ae Adar—so at least stable, if unpublished)

# Observed, poorly understood things

- other mutations - nasal, stop, mixed
- ablaut (when?)
- inflection of i-stem verbs
- details of tengwar modes
- nasal mutation from plural article (pheriannath)
- pronouns

# Debates

- ú- for negation

